38
00:02:59,206 --> 00:03:01,687
[SPEAKER_06]: Just briefly, this is the open meeting law.

39
00:03:01,827 --> 00:03:04,108
[SPEAKER_06]: It's been extended to March 31st, 2023.

40
00:03:04,208 --> 00:03:21,074
[SPEAKER_06]: Just to brief, the use of Zoom complies with the law's requirement to provide live adequate alternate means of public access to the deliberations of the public body instead of holding meetings in a public place that is open and physically accessible to the public.

41
00:03:23,298 --> 00:03:25,939
[SPEAKER_06]: So CDBG, what is it?

42
00:03:26,580 --> 00:03:29,301
[SPEAKER_06]: Community Development Block Grant, CDBG.

43
00:03:29,822 --> 00:03:33,224
[SPEAKER_06]: It's a program established by HUD, which is the U.S.

44
00:03:33,244 --> 00:03:38,807
[SPEAKER_06]: Department of Housing and Urban Development, and this grant has been around a long time, since 1974.

45
00:03:39,087 --> 00:03:44,471
[SPEAKER_06]: The grant benefits low to moderate income persons.

46
00:03:45,331 --> 00:03:54,225
[SPEAKER_06]: It's a flexible annual grant for entitlement communities so Medford would be an entitlement community, which means we get our money directly from HUD.

47
00:03:57,008 --> 00:04:09,613
[SPEAKER_06]: uses include public facilities, parks, public service agencies, many of you are from here, housing and specifically affordable housing and economic development.

48
00:04:10,653 --> 00:04:22,778
[SPEAKER_06]: So any project or activity we're using the CDBG funds for, they must prove and they must show that they benefit at least 51% of LMI or low moderate income persons.

49
00:04:23,998 --> 00:04:26,359
[SPEAKER_06]: And I will show you what those numbers are.

50
00:04:26,379 --> 00:04:36,403
[SPEAKER_06]: And just to add in, when we say LMI persons, 51%, those also have to be Medford residents for this grant.

51
00:04:37,184 --> 00:04:43,606
[SPEAKER_06]: So we actually, this year, for the first time in a while, we already know what our grant will be starting July 1st.

52
00:04:44,346 --> 00:04:50,209
[SPEAKER_06]: It's a little bit less than it was last year, unfortunately, but that number's about 1.4 million.

53
00:04:53,091 --> 00:05:02,140
[SPEAKER_06]: And what we get a lot of comments on is the public services, and so the public services is capped at 15% of our total award so that 15% is going to be over this 1.4.

54
00:05:11,369 --> 00:05:14,310
[SPEAKER_06]: Oh my God, there we go.

55
00:05:14,950 --> 00:05:21,411
[SPEAKER_06]: So low to moderate income, these were effective back in April 18th, 2022.

56
00:05:22,212 --> 00:05:25,852
[SPEAKER_06]: We never really have an exact date of when they will be updated.

57
00:05:26,233 --> 00:05:28,513
[SPEAKER_06]: Usually it will be sometime in April.

58
00:05:29,293 --> 00:05:36,175
[SPEAKER_06]: So for the new program year, these numbers are going to change most likely, and most likely they will increase.

59
00:05:37,215 --> 00:05:48,118
[SPEAKER_06]: But for CDBG purposes and LMI purposes, the most important one to really look at here is the blue highlighted one, where it says 80%.

60
00:05:48,978 --> 00:05:56,400
[SPEAKER_06]: And the way to read this is that if you're a single person in a family, your income has to be below the $78,300.

61
00:05:56,540 --> 00:05:58,461
[SPEAKER_06]: If there's two people in the home, $89,500 and so on.

62
00:06:08,950 --> 00:06:22,097
[SPEAKER_06]: Um, I know this is tough to see this is on our website on the city's website and our page specifically what the low and moderate income areas in Medford are and they're kind of this peachy orange shaded.

63
00:06:22,117 --> 00:06:30,601
[SPEAKER_06]: Um, and I know it's hard to see but when you if you are interested, we can get you Why is it small instead of being

64
00:06:36,348 --> 00:06:42,273
[SPEAKER_06]: So this is tough, but on the website, you'd be able to kind of zoom in a little bit better.

65
00:06:46,956 --> 00:06:53,341
[SPEAKER_06]: So this is just our kind of timeline we work with every year, the action plan and funding process.

66
00:06:54,262 --> 00:07:01,487
[SPEAKER_06]: So the action plan is submitted every year in May, and the program year will begin on July 1st and run to the following June 30th.

67
00:07:03,028 --> 00:07:07,330
[SPEAKER_06]: Our office creates a plan with the mayor that outlines the priorities for the upcoming year.

68
00:07:08,830 --> 00:07:16,833
[SPEAKER_06]: We also seek requests for proposals from public service agencies, which we did back in February, and we are reviewing those now.

69
00:07:18,473 --> 00:07:26,596
[SPEAKER_06]: We have a draft plan that's available for 30 days, and that'll be sometime in mid-April, and that's available for comment.

70
00:07:28,216 --> 00:07:32,881
[SPEAKER_06]: comments do have to be in writing and I will share my information at the end of this.

71
00:07:34,302 --> 00:07:39,087
[SPEAKER_06]: There's a committee of the whole meeting scheduled tentatively for April 18th.

72
00:07:40,409 --> 00:07:43,692
[SPEAKER_06]: This will be posted when there's an exact date.

73
00:07:43,752 --> 00:07:50,239
[SPEAKER_06]: This meeting's for public service agencies to present their programs and discuss their applications with the city council.

74
00:07:51,280 --> 00:07:55,550
[SPEAKER_06]: And then finally, we have a public hearing with the city council that's in early May.

75
00:07:56,291 --> 00:08:01,643
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's where we request that the council approve the plan that we've created with the mayor.

76
00:08:04,802 --> 00:08:08,185
[SPEAKER_06]: So just talking a little bit more about public service activities.

77
00:08:08,485 --> 00:08:13,069
[SPEAKER_06]: So as I said previously, it's capped at 15% of the total award.

78
00:08:14,029 --> 00:08:21,555
[SPEAKER_06]: So this year, we do have a little bit of a decrease and that cap is 213,547.

79
00:08:22,676 --> 00:08:30,141
[SPEAKER_06]: For public service activities, eligible programs have to demonstrate that the primary benefit is to low to moderate income residents.

80
00:08:31,842 --> 00:08:35,204
[SPEAKER_06]: And public services, there's a wide range of activities.

81
00:08:35,824 --> 00:08:37,685
[SPEAKER_06]: I've listed a few of them here.

82
00:08:38,266 --> 00:08:39,566
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not all of them.

83
00:08:40,547 --> 00:08:49,031
[SPEAKER_06]: There's employment services, ESOL classes, childcare, health services, education programs.

84
00:08:49,752 --> 00:08:56,155
[SPEAKER_06]: There's different services for seniors and the disabled, for homeless persons and recreation.

85
00:08:59,668 --> 00:09:07,993
[SPEAKER_06]: And these are some of, these aren't everybody, but these are a few of the current public service activities that CDBG is funding.

86
00:09:08,974 --> 00:09:11,575
[SPEAKER_06]: There's a few different programs at the Council on Aging.

87
00:09:12,716 --> 00:09:21,681
[SPEAKER_06]: We fund some of the senior services program at the West Medford Community Center, the YMCA Mystic Community Market.

88
00:09:22,762 --> 00:09:26,925
[SPEAKER_06]: There's tuition assistance for afterschool program for Medford Public Schools.

89
00:09:27,785 --> 00:09:35,832
[SPEAKER_06]: SCM Transportation provides transportation for seniors and disabled for some grocery shopping and doctor's appointments.

90
00:09:36,952 --> 00:09:41,816
[SPEAKER_06]: Housing Families has a pro bono legal service that they help Medford families.

91
00:09:42,897 --> 00:09:47,080
[SPEAKER_06]: The Immigrant Learning Center, CDBG helps fund their ESOL classes.

92
00:09:48,061 --> 00:09:55,087
[SPEAKER_06]: Communitas has a recreation program and new this year was the ABCD Mobile Outreach Team.

93
00:09:58,612 --> 00:10:02,056
[SPEAKER_06]: And these are our other projects that we're doing.

94
00:10:03,777 --> 00:10:09,784
[SPEAKER_06]: We're currently installing a new apparatus floor at engine three, that's the fire station on Salem Street.

95
00:10:10,645 --> 00:10:13,968
[SPEAKER_06]: There are street and sidewalk improvements going on at Pinkert Street.

96
00:10:15,990 --> 00:10:20,415
[SPEAKER_06]: There is going to be design for more improvements at Gorley Road and Dwyer Circle.

97
00:10:21,576 --> 00:10:30,184
[SPEAKER_06]: And we've been doing and we're still doing some tree stump removal and subsequent tree planting in different LMI areas throughout the city.

98
00:10:31,165 --> 00:10:34,448
[SPEAKER_06]: And also some upgrades at Morrison and Logan Park.

99
00:10:38,859 --> 00:10:39,760
[SPEAKER_06]: And upcoming.

100
00:10:40,581 --> 00:10:47,870
[SPEAKER_06]: These are just a few things we're looking, we'll be doing some more street and sidewalk and some intersection improvements throughout the city.

101
00:10:49,652 --> 00:10:52,375
[SPEAKER_06]: Some ADA compliance at some of the parks.

102
00:10:53,576 --> 00:10:55,919
[SPEAKER_06]: Also some upgrades for the McGlynn playground.

103
00:10:57,040 --> 00:11:01,343
[SPEAKER_06]: as well as a second phase of the community garden at LaPreeze Village.

104
00:11:02,183 --> 00:11:06,926
[SPEAKER_06]: We did that last year, and it was met with great promise.

105
00:11:07,026 --> 00:11:08,267
[SPEAKER_06]: People were really happy with it.

106
00:11:08,947 --> 00:11:11,729
[SPEAKER_06]: So we're going to add some additional beds there.

107
00:11:12,729 --> 00:11:18,993
[SPEAKER_06]: And we will continue and finish up this year the stump removal and the tree planting.

108
00:11:22,606 --> 00:11:24,308
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's it for right now.

109
00:11:24,909 --> 00:11:40,808
[SPEAKER_06]: I'd like to open it up for any comments, suggestions, questions you may have, you know, what you think the priorities should be, you know, where should we focus our resources, if there's any needs you feel aren't being met.

