00:21:17,871 --> 00:21:19,913
[SPEAKER_11]: Terry, Terry Carter, you're raising your hand.

215
00:21:20,414 --> 00:21:21,335
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, thank you.

216
00:21:22,556 --> 00:21:33,925
[SPEAKER_01]: Obviously echoing the note of thanks from all of our sister agencies out there who have been benefiting from the CBBG grant over many years now.

217
00:21:34,265 --> 00:21:40,630
[SPEAKER_01]: And here at the community center, elder services is a principal recipient.

218
00:21:41,270 --> 00:21:49,477
[SPEAKER_01]: And for us, the mission has really been one of, I call it isolation busting.

219
00:21:50,269 --> 00:22:14,598
[SPEAKER_01]: Because one of the things that COVID has done, and this is no secret to anybody, it has made people very, very reticent about being out and around other folks, and particularly seniors, because they're in that, obviously, that protected class where health impacts and those sorts of things keep them from feeling as comfortable as they might otherwise with being around other people.

220
00:22:15,198 --> 00:22:20,321
[SPEAKER_01]: But our open doors have really been a boon to the local community.

221
00:22:20,921 --> 00:22:29,126
[SPEAKER_01]: And we're seeing more people, we're seeing different people come through our doors with the sole mission of not being alone.

222
00:22:29,546 --> 00:22:31,988
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's really a beautiful thing.

223
00:22:32,048 --> 00:22:38,512
[SPEAKER_01]: I had the opportunity today to, with help from

224
00:22:39,935 --> 00:22:53,898
[SPEAKER_01]: The principal at the method vocational technical high school take a group of, I think there were 10 or 11 ladies to the Priscilla salon, which is the beauty salon at the school.

225
00:22:54,601 --> 00:23:06,766
[SPEAKER_01]: for manicures, you know, and it seemed on its face like a fairly simple thing, but there's a lot of joy in those kinds of kindred activities now that some of the doors are beginning to open again.

226
00:23:07,587 --> 00:23:18,271
[SPEAKER_01]: And so for us, we feel like we opened our doors early, you know, maybe we threw a little bit of caution to the wind, but hopefully not too much.

227
00:23:19,112 --> 00:23:21,873
[SPEAKER_01]: And the impact has been measurable

228
00:23:22,625 --> 00:23:37,520
[SPEAKER_01]: And in potent in terms of busting isolation in the greater West Memphis community and we do see folks from outside of you know the three streets that we originally that originally comprised the black community.

229
00:23:38,040 --> 00:23:42,043
[SPEAKER_01]: in West Medford, but it's really a beautiful thing.

230
00:23:42,083 --> 00:23:43,404
[SPEAKER_01]: There's a lot of joy in it.

231
00:23:44,225 --> 00:23:52,551
[SPEAKER_01]: Anybody who comes by the community center on any given day, Tuesday through Thursday, finds that there's a lot of laughter and a whole bunch of shenanigans.

232
00:23:52,651 --> 00:24:05,080
[SPEAKER_01]: So it's just a good thing to help these organizations, and there are a lot of them here in the room and a lot more that are out there, keep their doors open.

233
00:24:05,711 --> 00:24:16,501
[SPEAKER_01]: and keep battling the things that we're battling, isolation, homelessness, you know, some of the problems that, you know, the immigrant communities have, language issues.

234
00:24:17,002 --> 00:24:27,792
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's, we're just really, we feel privileged to be part of this network, this web that is doing this for the communities of Medford and beyond.

235
00:24:28,312 --> 00:24:29,033
[SPEAKER_01]: So thank you.

236
00:24:29,433 --> 00:24:30,995
[SPEAKER_01]: We really, really appreciate

